### Describe the bug

Not sure if this is a bug, or a missing feature, or if I'm just doing something wrong, but I'd like to get the discussion started.

We're currently implementing a controller-based ASP.NET Core WebAPI using the latest .NET version (10.0.6) with the relatively new OpenAPI support provided by Microsoft, i.e. the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi` and `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Server` NuGet packages.

We also set property `OpenApiGenerateDocuments=true` in our `.csproj` file to get an OpenAPI JSON document (used by external client applications) generated at build time.

Now, when I combine this with `Asp.Versioning.Mvc` (with our without `Asp.Versioning.Mvc.ApiExplorer` and `Asp.Versioning.OpenApi`), results are not as expected. With no further additions, the version tag in the routes is not resolved as expected.

Let's say I have this controller...

```csharp
[ApiVersion(1.0)]
[ApiVersion(1.1)]
[ApiVersion(2.0)]
[ApiController]
[Route("api/v{version:apiVersion}/[controller]")]
public class WeatherForecastController : ControllerBase
{
    [HttpGet(Name = "GetWeatherForecast")]
    public IEnumerable<WeatherForecast> Get()
    {
        return ...;
    }
}
```

...and this setup in `Program.cs`...

```csharp
var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services
    .AddApiVersioning()
    .AddMvc();

builder.Services.AddControllers();
builder.Services.AddOpenApi();

var app = builder.Build();

// Configure the HTTP request pipeline.
if (app.Environment.IsDevelopment())
{
    app.MapOpenApi();
}

app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
```

...then the generated OpenAPI JSON file contains this:

```json
{
  "openapi": "3.1.1",
  "info": {
    "title": "AspVersioningTest | v1",
    "version": "1.0.0"
  },
  "paths": {
    "/api/v{version}/WeatherForecast": {
      "get": {
        "tags": [
          "WeatherForecast"
        ],
        "operationId": "GetWeatherForecast",
      ...
    }
 }
```

The problem is the `/api/v{version}/WeatherForecast` path. The `v{version}` placeholder is not resolved as expected.

Now when I add `AddApiExplorer` and/or `AddOpenApi` (which implies `AddApiExplorer`) in `Program.cs` like this...

```csharp
builder.Services
    .AddApiVersioning()
    .AddMvc()
    .AddApiExplorer()
    .AddOpenApi();
```

...then the auto-generated OpenAPI JSON file is more or less empty:

```json
{
  "openapi": "3.1.1",
  "info": {
    "title": "AspVersioningTest | v1",
    "version": "1.0.0"
  },
  "paths": { }
}
```

Looks like the Microsoft OpenAPI libraries and the Asp.Versioning libraries are conflicting. I would have expected that they somehow work "hand-in-hand".

### Expected Behavior

I would have expected multiple paths like e.g.
- `/api/v1/WeatherForecast`
- `/api/v1.0/WeatherForecast` 
- `/api/v1.1/WeatherForecast` 
- `/api/v2/WeatherForecast`
- `/api/v2.0/WeatherForecast`

### Steps To Reproduce

Here's my little playground project: [AspVersioningTest.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/27126246/AspVersioningTest.zip)

